'''Diplomatic capital''' refers to the trust, goodwill, and influence which a [[diplomat]], or a state represented by its diplomats, has within [[international diplomacy]]. According to political scientist Rebecca Adler-Nissen, diplomatic capital is a kind of [[currency]] that can be traded in [[Diplomacy#Negotiations|diplomatic negotiations]] and that is increased when positive ″social competences, reputation and personal authority" are portrayed.<ref name="czulda-madej-p156">{{cite book|author1=Robert Czulda|author2=Marek Madej|title=Newcomers No More? Contemporary NATO and the Future of the Enlargement from the Perspective of “Post-Cold War” Members|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IdASBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA156|publisher=Instytut Badań nad Stosunkami Międzynarodowymi|isbn=978-83-62784-04-2|pages=156}}</ref>
== Accumulation and loss == Diplomatic capital can be accumulated for example by economic cooperation<ref name="sato-limaye-2006-p200">{{cite book|author1=Yoichiro Sato|author2=Satu Limaye|title=Japan in a Dynamic Asia: Coping with the New Security Challenges|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HeNuAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA200|date=25 May 2006|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-7391-5669-8|pages=200}}</ref> and by contributions to the solution of [[International crisis|international crises]],<ref name="brodsky-rein-2012-p278">{{cite book|author1=Adriana Brodsky|author2=Raanan Rein|title=The New Jewish Argentina: Facets of Jewish Experiences in the Southern Cone|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XTkyAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA278|date=28 September 2012|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-23728-5|pages=278}}</ref> It is strengthened when in other countries the sentiment prevails that the interests of a state or the diplomats representing it are aligned with their own interests. Conversely, it can be squandered when a country engages in a confrontation, an armed conflict or a war, if that is perceived as unjust or at odds with the interests of others.<ref name="kiesling-2006-p277">{{cite book|author=John Brady Kiesling|title=Diplomacy Lessons: Realism for an Unloved Superpower|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dY6MlrWbLeUC&pg=PA277|year=2006|publisher=Potomac Books, Inc.|isbn=978-1-59797-017-4|pages=277}}</ref><ref name="bow-lennox-2008-p73">{{cite book|author1=Brian J. Bow|author2=Patrick Lennox|title=An Independent Foreign Policy for Canada?: Challenges and Choices for the Future|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y3BD6TsvtGQC&pg=PA73|year=2008|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-0-8020-9690-6|pages=73}}</ref>
Diplomatic capital is also linked to the extent of enforcement of [[human rights]].<ref name="o'flaherty-etal-2011-p7">{{cite book|author1=Michael O'Flaherty|author2=Zdzislaw Kedzia|author3=Amrei Müller|author4=George Ulrich|title=Human Rights Diplomacy: Contemporary Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5g8bJoZ252gC&pg=PR7|date=28 October 2011|publisher=Martinus Nijhoff Publishers|isbn=90-04-19516-5|pages=7}}</ref>
