{{Infobox treaty | name = Nationwide Ceasefire Agreement | long_name = Nationwide Ceasefire Agreement between the Government of the Republic of the Union of Myanmar and the Ethnic Armed Organisations | image = | image_size = | caption = | type = | date_drafted = {{Start date|2015|3|31|df=y}} | date_signed = {{Start date|2015|10|15|df=y}} | location_signed = [[Naypyidaw]], [[Myanmar]] | date_sealed = | date_effective = | condition_effective = | date_expiration = | negotiators = | signatories = * {{flagdeco|Myanmar}} [[Cabinet of Myanmar|Myanmar]] * {{flagicon image|Fighting Peacock Flag.png}} [[All Burma Students' Democratic Front|ABSDF]] * {{flagicon image|Arakan Liberation Party flag.png}} [[Arakan Liberation Party]] * {{flagicon image|Chin National Army Flag.svg}} [[Chin National Front]] * {{flagicon image|Flag of DKBA-5 (Buddhist).png}} [[DKBA-5]] * {{flagicon image|Flag of the Karen National Union.svg}} [[Karen National Union]] * {{flagicon image|Karen National Liberation Army flag.png}} [[KNU/KNLA Peace Council]] * {{flagicon image|Lahu flag.svg}} [[Lahu Democratic Union]] * {{flagicon image|New Mon State Party flag.png}} [[New Mon State Party]] * {{flagicon image|Pa-o nationality flag.png}} [[Pa-O National Liberation Army]] * {{nowrap|{{flagicon image|SSA-S.svg}} [[Restoration Council of Shan State]]}} | depositor = Government of Myanmar | citations = | languages = [[English language|English]], [[Burmese language|Burmese]] | wikisource = }}
The '''Nationwide Ceasefire Agreement''' ({{lang-my|တစ်နိုင်ငံလုံး ပစ်ခတ်တိုက်ခိုက်မှု ရပ်စဲရေးသဘောတူစာချုပ်}}; [[Abbreviation|abbreviated]] '''NCA''') was a landmark [[ceasefire]] agreement between the [[Cabinet of Myanmar|government of Myanmar]] and representatives of various ethnic insurgent groups, officially known as "ethnic armed organisations" (EAOs) by the government. The draft was agreed upon by a majority of the invited parties on 31 March 2015,<ref>{{cite web|title=Myanmar's Nationwide Ceasefire Agreement - Institute for Security and Development Policy|url=http://isdp.eu/publication/myanmars-nationwide-ceasefire-agreement/|website=Institute for Security and Development Policy|accessdate=15 October 2017}}</ref> and the agreement was signed by [[President of Myanmar|President]] [[Thein Sein]] on 15 October 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Myanmar signs ceasefire with eight armed groups|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-myanmar-politics/myanmar-signs-ceasefire-with-eight-armed-groups-idUSKCN0S82MR20151015|accessdate=15 October 2017|work=Reuters|date=14 October 2015}}</ref> The signing was witnessed by observers and delegates from the [[United Nations]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[Norway]], [[Japan]] and the [[United States]].<ref name="blogs.cfr.org">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.cfr.org/asia/2015/10/07/myanmars-cease-fire-deal-comes-up-short/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009042537/http://blogs.cfr.org/asia/2015/10/07/myanmars-cease-fire-deal-comes-up-short/ |archive-date=9 October 2015 |dead-url=yes |title=Asia Unbound » Myanmar’s Cease-Fire Deal Comes up Short |accessdate=21 October 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name="Ray Pagnucco and Jennifer Peters">{{cite news|title=Myanmar's National Ceasefire Agreement isn't all that national|url=https://news.vice.com/article/myanmars-national-ceasefire-agreement-to-end-68-year-civil-war-isnt-all-that-national|accessdate=18 October 2015|newspaper=Vice News|date=15 October 2015|author=Ray Pagnucco and Jennifer Peters}}</ref> A ceremony is held by the government annually on the anniversary of the signing of the agreement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thiha|first1=Amara|title=On the second anniversary of the NCA, is Myanmar keeping peace on track?|url=https://frontiermyanmar.net/en/on-the-second-anniversary-of-the-nca-is-myanmar-keeping-peace-on-track|accessdate=15 October 2017|work=Frontier Myanmar|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nationwide Ceasefire Agreement is a Forlorn Hope|url=https://www.irrawaddy.com/opinion/guest-column/nationwide-ceasefire-agreement-forlorn-hope.html|accessdate=15 October 2017|work=The Irrawaddy|date=12 October 2017}}</ref>
The government of Myanmar originally sent invitations to 15 different ethnic insurgent groups, inviting them to participate in long-term peace negotiations with them. However, seven of those invited declined or dropped out during negotiations due to perceived unfairness.<ref>{{cite news|title=Myanmar Signs Historic Cease-Fire Deal With Eight Ethnic Armies|url=http://www.rfa.org/english/news/myanmar/deal-10152015175051.html|accessdate=15 October 2017|work=Radio Free Asia|language=en}}</ref>
The [[Lahu Democratic Union]] and the [[New Mon State Party]] later joined the ceasefire<ref>{{cite news|last1=Zaw Lin|first1=Nyein|last2=Min Mang|first2=Lun|title=New Mon State Party, Lahu Democratic Union to sign ceasefire|url=https://www.mmtimes.com/news/new-mon-state-party-lahu-democratic-union-sign-ceasefire.html|accessdate=28 March 2018|work=The Myanmar Times|date=24 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> and signed the agreement on 13 February 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=2 groups join Myanmar government's peace process|url=https://apnews.com/e668736f3c4b44cfa310addefd4da1e3|accessdate=28 March 2018|work=AP News|date=13 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=New Mon State Party and Lahu Democratic Union sign NCA|url=http://www.president-office.gov.mm/en/?q=issues/peace/id-8468|publisher=Office of the President of Myanmar|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Analysis: A Win for Peace Commission as Mon, Lahu Groups Sign NCA|url=https://www.irrawaddy.com/news/burma/analysis-win-peace-commission-mon-lahu-groups-sign-nca.html|accessdate=28 March 2018|work=The Irrawaddy|date=13 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NCA signing ceremony for NMSP, LDU to take place on 13 Feb|url=http://www.mizzima.com/news-domestic/nca-signing-ceremony-nmsp-ldu-take-place-13-feb|accessdate=28 March 2018|work=Mizzima|date=6 February 2018|language=en}}</ref>
